<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Elster_A3_Alpha_Type_A30_electricity_meter_collector.jpeg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Each local mesh networked smart meter has a hub such as this Elster A3 Type A30 which interfaces 900MHZ smart meters to the metering automation server via landline.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>A <b>smart meter</b> generally refers to a type of advanced meter (usually an <a href="/wiki/Electrical_meter" title="Electrical meter" class="mw-redirect">electrical meter</a>) that identifies consumption in more detail than a conventional meter; and optionally, but generally, communicates that information via some <a href="/wiki/Computer_networking" title="Computer networking">network</a> back to the local <a href="/wiki/Public_utility" title="Public utility">utility</a> for monitoring and billing purposes (<a href="/wiki/Telemetering" title="Telemetering" class="mw-redirect">telemetering</a>).</p>
